<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Health Select Committee Inquiry on Public Expenditure on Social Care</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from Scope (PEX 0022)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">About Scope</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1.1 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Scope exists to make this country a better place for disabled people and their families. We do this by running a range of services, raising awareness of the issues </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that disabled people face and influencing change across society.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We provide support, advice and information for more than a quarter of a million disabled people and their family members every year.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1.2 Scope welcomes the opportunity </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to submit written evid</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ence to the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Committee’s Inquiry and would be happy to provide oral evidence if requested.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Our submission focuses on the questions relating to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">public expenditure on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">social care.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Background</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.1 Social care is the support that enables disabled people to liv</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e independently and with dignity. It supports</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">them to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">do essential day to day tasks such as washing, dress</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ing, eating as well as living independent lives in their community.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.2 Working aged disabled people make up one third of social care users - i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n 2012</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">/13</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, there were </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">434</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">775</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> working-aged disabled people in the social care system - out of a total of 1,332,995</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. However, demographic changes mean the numbers of working-aged disabled people needing care are projected to rise by 9.2%</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> from 2010 to 2020. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">3. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The impact on the provision of adult social care of the 2010 spending review settlement and the ability of local authorities to make the necessary efficiency savings</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.1 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Scope welcome</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the Government’s commitment to investing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">an extra </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">£1bn in social ca</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">re in the 2010 Spending Review</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> which was an important recognition of the increasing pressures on the social care system.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.2 However as funding for social care is not ring-fenced, th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is investment must be seen in the context </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of a 33% cut in local </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">councils’ budgets by 2014/15</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and the chronic long term </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">underfunding of the social care system</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.3. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ver the past three years, £2.68 billion has been cut from adult social care - 20 per cent of net spending</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> With</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the increasing numbers of disabled adults who need care and support</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">we are concerned that the Government’s investment will not ensure the sustainable funding of the social care system</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As a result of these </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">pressures</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, alongside an ageing population, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">many local authorities have been raising the threshold at which disabled people become eligible for support. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">However this trend began even before 2010. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In 2005, 50% of local authorities set their eligibility criteria at ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Moderate’ needs but</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">b</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">y 2012, 84% ha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d set their eligibility criteria at</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">higher ‘substantial’ needs</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, meaning t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hat s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ince 200</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">7/</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">8 the number of people using care has </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">gradually </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">fallen by at least </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">347</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,000</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (see table below)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As a result, just 14% of those with ‘moderate’ FACS needs are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">receiving care</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, while </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">at least</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 800,000 people with care needs are not receiving any support at all</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Change in number of social care recipients</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:100%"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:11.74%"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Year</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:17.64%"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Number (000s)</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:17.64%"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Year-on-year change (000s)</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; 